<p class="basic-text"><span>Faculty members prepare students for the job market by combining class work with actual experience. The primary college outlet for student journalism is NewsNetNebraska, the college’s student-produced website. In addition, students have the opportunity to work for the Nebraska News Service and The Daily Nebraskan and to participate in depth reports, international photo project<del class="del cts-2" title="Deleted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:45pm" data-cid="3" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633112289"> </del>s<ins class="ins cts-2" title="Inserted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:45pm" data-cid="4" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633113956"> </ins>and many other print and online news services on campus<ins class="ins cts-2" title="Inserted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:45pm" data-cid="5" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633123179">.</ins> The journalism program emphasizes professional internships, and students in recent years have worked at such media organizations as ABC News, The New York Times, The Washington Post, The Dallas Morning News, <del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:12pm" data-cid="63" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390335156998">Fox News,</del> The Omaha World-Herald, The Des Moines Register, The Norfolk Daily News and The St. Paul Pioneer Press, as well as numerous other newspapers and online publications. The college also has partnerships with two media organizations that offer paid internships during the school year in Lincoln.</span></p>
<p class="basic-text"><span>The Omaha World-Herald, Nebraska’s largest newspaper, works with the college to teach a course called “The Real World” in which World-Herald staff members offer students insight into working for a newspaper. Each semester the World-Herald chooses four students to be “fellows,” and they work in the newspaper’s Lincoln bureau.</span></p>
<p class="basic-text"><span>Additionally, journalism students achieve national recognition by successfully competing in such programs as the Hearst Journalism Awards, the Dow Jones News Fund editing internship program, the Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Awards and the Society of Professional Journalists’ Mark of Excellence Awards.</span></p>
<p class="basic-text"><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:07pm" data-cid="25" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390334856816">The College of Journalism and Mass Communications offers three majors: broadcasting, journalism, and the combined area of advertising and public relations.</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:07pm" data-cid="25" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390334856816">The journalism curriculum, combined from broadcasting and traditional print journalism programs, is built on intensive reporting and writing. All students are required to take courses in reporting and writing, copy editing, visual literacy, mass media law, contemporary issues in mass media and multimedia journalism. Elective choices include courses in magazine writing, depth reporting, feature writing, sports writing, business writing, science writing, photography, design, broadcast news writing, videography and advanced editing. Students may also choose an emphasis in broadcast production, in which they will enroll in courses in audio and video production.</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:07pm" data-cid="25" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390334856816">Many of the journalism faculty members have extensive industry experience at media organizations such as The Wall Street Journal, The Miami Herald, The Detroit News, ABC News and The New York Times. The faculty continues to be connected to the industry, and its members are actively involved in professional media organizations. Students, likewise, are encouraged to further their professional goals through participation in student organizations such as the Alpha Epsilon Rho national broadcasting society, the Society of Professional Journalists, the Radio Television Digital News Association and the American Copy Editors Association.</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:07pm" data-cid="25" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390334856816">Faculty members prepare students for the job market by combining class work with actual experience. The primary college outlet for student journalism is NewsNetNebraska, the college’s student-produced website. In addition, students have the opportunity to work on the Star City News, a weekly television news broadcast; KRNU, a professionally managed FM radio station; and regularly scheduled magazines, which publish the work of depth reporting and photography students.</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:07pm" data-cid="25" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390334856816">The journalism program places a great deal of importance on professional internships, and students in recent years have worked at such media organizations as ABC News, The New York Times, The Washington Post, The Dallas Morning News, Fox News, The Omaha World-Herald, The Des Moines Register, The Norfolk Daily News and The St. Paul Pioneer Press, as well as numerous other newspapers and local television stations. The college also has partnerships with two media organizations that offer paid internships during the school year in Lincoln.</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:07pm" data-cid="25" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390334856816">The Omaha World-Herald, Nebraska’s largest newspaper, works with the college to teach a course called “The Real World” in which World-Herald staff members offer students insight into working for a newspaper. Each semester the World-Herald chooses four students to be “fellows,” and they work in the newspaper’s Lincoln bureau.</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:07pm" data-cid="25" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390334856816">Additionally, journalism students achieve national recognition by successfully competing in such programs as the Hearst Journalism Awards, Sigma Delta Chi Awards, the Dow Jones News Fund editing internship program, the Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Awards and the Society of Professional Journalists’ Mark of Excellence Awards.</del></p>
<p class="content-box-h-1">MAJOR REQUIREMENTS</p>
<p class="title-1">Specific Major Requirements</p>
<p class="basic-text"><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:13pm" data-cid="5" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390335231222"> </del><span>The courses required for a 36-hour major in journalism are as follows:</span></p>
<p class="MsoList"><span>JOMC 101, JOMC 160, JOMC 486 and JOMC 487; JOUR 201, JOUR 202, JOUR 302, JOUR 304, and either JOUR 446 or JOUR 450. In addition, students select 9 hours of electives from advertising and public relations, broadcasting and/or journalism.</span></p>
<p class="header-paragraph"><span>Students may complete two majors in the College of Journalism and Mass Communications by completing all requirements for each major; however, the second major in the college will not take the place of a concentration or any of the 72 hours required outside the college.</span></p>
<p class="header-paragraph"><span><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:13pm" data-cid="7" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390335233908"> </del></span></p>
<p class="header-paragraph"><span>Graduating seniors also must complete JOMC 98, Senior Assessment. Typically, JOMC 98 is taken in the last semester; however, seniors who have completed all courses for the major may take it two semesters before graduation.</span></p>
<p class="basic-text"><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:13pm" data-cid="3" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390335200941">The courses required for a 36-hour major in journalism are as follows:</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:13pm" data-cid="3" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390335200941">JOMC 101, JOMC 160, JOMC 486 and JOMC 487; JOUR 201, JOUR 202, JOUR 302, JOUR 304, and either JOUR 446 or JOUR 450. In addition, students select 9 hours of electives from advertising and public relations, broadcasting and/or journalism.</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:13pm" data-cid="3" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390335200941">Students may complete two majors in the College of Journalism and Mass Communications by completing all requirements for each major; however, the second major in the college will not take the place of a concentration or any of the 72 hours required outside the college.</del><del class="del cts-1" title="Deleted by Charlyne Berens - 01/21/2014 2:13pm" data-cid="3" data-userid="295" data-username="Charlyne Berens" data-time="1390335200941">Graduating seniors also must complete JOMC 98, Senior Assessment. Typically, JOMC 98 is taken in the last semester; however, seniors who have completed all courses for the major may take it in the term preceding graduation.</del></p>
<p class="content-box-h-1">ADDITIONAL MAJOR REQUIREMENTS</p>
<p></p>
<p><span><span class="title-2">Internship</span> <ins class="ins cts-2" title="Inserted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:52pm" data-cid="3" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633560183">P</ins><del class="del cts-2" title="Deleted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:52pm" data-cid="2" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633559227">p</del>olicy</span></p>
<p class="basic-text"><span>Students may be able to earn credit for internships under certain circumstances. Please go to the college website and find the Internship Policy under the Student Services tab.  </span></p>
<p class="title-2"><span>Credit in <ins class="ins cts-2" title="Inserted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:53pm" data-cid="5" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633588079">S</ins><del class="del cts-2" title="Deleted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:53pm" data-cid="4" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633587432">s</del>pecial <ins class="ins cts-2" title="Inserted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:53pm" data-cid="7" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633592039">E</ins><del class="del cts-2" title="Deleted by Judy Anderson - 02/5/2014 2:53pm" data-cid="6" data-userid="1138" data-username="Judy Anderson" data-time="1391633591456">e</del>xperiences</span></p>
<p>Students may earn up to six credit hours toward the degree in some courses: Jacht, National Student Advertising Competition, photojournalism reports, depth reports and others. Students may repeat the same course again for additional credit hours, but those credits will not count toward the degree inside or outside the major. Talk with an academic adviser for further information or specific questions.<span></span></p>
